    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-11-01T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-11-01T19:00:00-05:00" n="491"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d491">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">868.24/89: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Greece</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacVeagh</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Athens</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-11-02T02:00:00+02:00"
                            >November 2, 1940—2 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 1:50 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>275. Baker<note n="70" xml:id="d491fn70">Maj. Joseph K. Baker, Military Attaché
                        in Greece.</note> has been informed by the British Military Attaché who has
                    already taken up quarters with the Greek General Staff<note n="71"
                        xml:id="d491fn71">Following outbreak of war between Italy and Greece,
                        October 28, 1940. For correspondence on this subject, see <ref
                            target="#pg_524">pp. 524</ref> ff.</note> that the Greek Army is short
                    of anti-aircraft ammunition and desires 50,000 rounds of type Krupp 88
                    millimeters fuse type UZS–30 weight 385 kilograms. The Attaché has wired London
                    to know whether this can be obtained anywhere in the Western Hemisphere either
                    complete ammunition or a fuse suitable of being adapted. He is confident that
                    his Government will soon communicate with Washington and suggests that a
                    preliminary investigation of opportunities might be useful.</p>
                <p>I transmit this for the Department’s information and for such use as it may wish
                    to make of it.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">MacVeagh</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
